enth century is not generally associated with the formation of distinct generations. This book, therefore, charts new territory as an age cohort in Newcastle upon Tyne is followed from infancy to early adulthood,using their experiences to illuminate a national, and ultimately imperial, pattern of change. The chapters begin in the nurseries and schoolrooms in which formative years were spent and then traverse the volatile terrain of adolescence, before turning to the adult world of fashion and politics. This investigation uncovers the roots of a generational divide that spilled into the political arena during the parliamentary election of 1774. But more than that,it demonstrates that the interactions between age groups were central to major social and cultural developments in the eighteenth century and serves as a powerful reminder of the need to recognise that people lived throughnot in the past. BARBARA CROSBIE is Assistant Professor in Early Modern Social History at Durham University and co-edited (with Adrian Green) Economy and Culture in North-East England, 1500-1800 (Boydell Press, 2018).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEducation.-fast-(OCoLC)fst00902499. 0aEngland-Education-18th century. 0aEngland-Social life and customs-18th century. 0aEngland.-fast-(OCoLC)fst01219920. 0aEngland.-gnd. 0aGreat Britain-Politics and government-18th century. 0aGreat Britain.-fast-(OCoLC)fst01204623. 0aIntergenerational relationszEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aIntergenerational relations-England-History-18th century. 0aIntergenerational relations.-fast-(OCoLC)fst00976251. 0aManners and customs.-fast-(OCoLC)fst01007815. 0aPolitics and government.-fast-(OCoLC)fst01919741. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAge relations